'''''Mortville Manor''''' ('''''{{Lang-fr|Le Manoir de Mortevielle}}''''') is a [[point-and-click adventure game]] developed and published by [[Lankhor]] released in 1987 for [[Atari ST]]. The game was ported to the [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Amiga]] and [[Sinclair QL]]. An [[MS-DOS]] version was released in 1988 adapted by Clement Roques. ''Mortville Manor'' was the first game with [[speech synthesis]] and was sold 10,000 copies around [[Europe]].<ref name="MortMan-ACE">{{cite journal |date=October 1988 |title=ACE, Issue 013 |url=https://archive.org/stream/ace-magazine-13/ACE_Issue_13_1988_Oct#page/n103 |journal=[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]] |issue=13 |page=104 |access-date=September 18, 2017}}</ref>  ''Mortville Manor'' was followed by its sequel ''[[Maupiti Island (video game)|Maupiti Island]]''.
==Plot==
The game takes place in France in the 1950s.<ref name=":0" /> The plot begins in the office of Jérôme Lange, a famous private detective, who receives a letter from his childhood friend Julia Defranck, in which she writes that she is ill and asks him to investigate strange events at Mortville Manor. Upon arrival, Jérôme is informed of Julia's death with a storm approaching, and begins his search around the manor.

==Gameplay==
[[File:Mortville_Manor_Atari_ST_screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|The player can select Jérôme's next action using the drop-down menus (Atari ST screenshot).]]
''Mortville Manor'' is a [[First-person (video games)|first-person]] [[adventure game]] with a [[Point and click|point-and-click]] interface.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book |last=Jankowski |first=F |title=Settling accounts with France's historical past on the example of Lankhor games |publisher=The Polish Journal of Game Studies |year=2019 |isbn= |language=pl}}</ref> The player takes on the role of Jérôme Lange, observing the world though [[First-person narrative|first-person perspective]]. The player can move around Mortevielle's mansion by using the toolbar at the top of the screen and giving the hero commands from the drop-down lists.<ref name=":0" /> The player also has the opportunity to interrogate individual residents of the Mortevielle estate, who move freely around the game.

== Development ==
The first version of ''Mortville Manor was'' released for the [[Sinclair QL]] and was developed by two employees of the Kyilkhor studio who operated with the Pyramide publishing house Bruno Gourier and Bernard Grelaud. Gourier and Grelaud teamed up with siblings Béatrice and Jean-Luc Langlois and started their own company [[Lankhor]]. With its technical qualities and attractive price, the [[Atari ST]] was gaining momentum in [[France]] and the company decides to develop for this machine as a priority.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Desktop |first=Steph |date=May 22, 2017 |title=Le Manoir de Mortevielle de Lankhor - il y a 30 ans débutait sur ATARI ST une nouvelle génération du jeu vidéo d'aventure |trans-title=Le Manoir de Mortevielle de Lankhor - 30 years ago, a new generation of adventure video games began on the ATARI ST |url=https://www.rom-game.fr/news/2664-Manoir+de+Mortevielle+Lankhor.html |access-date=2023-05-21 |website=Rom Game |language=fr}}</ref> ''Mortville Manor'' was released for the Atari ST in 1987. The Langlois siblings developed a [[Speech synthesis|speech synthesizer]] that read other characters speeches. Dominique Sablons responded with a complete redesign of the [[Amiga]] and [[MS-DOS]] graphics.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |date=January 25, 2019 |title=Abandonware France, #MadeInFrance 07 : From Mortevielle to Maupiti |url=https://www.abandonware-france.org/ltf_abandon/ltf_infos_fic.php?id=103094 |access-date=2023-05-21 |website=Abandonware France |publisher=Hoagie |language=fr}}</ref>

